. 75. Right antenna, dorsal view. 76. Male right protibia. 77. Male right metafemur and metatibia. 78. Aedeagus, dorsal view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Fig. 78), 0.4 mm (Fig. 76), 0.5 mm (Fig. 75), 0.75 mm (Fig. 77).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,1906,2010]" lastBlockId="30.[151,1436,152,758]" lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="31" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,488,1906,1932]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Diagnostic description.</emphasis>
Shining, reddish brown except elytra which are yellowish with narrow darker lateral margins. Length of pronotum + elytra = 2.6–2.9 mm (males). Head irregularly, sparsely punctate. Pronotum widest near middle, sides obtusely rounded at middle, basal angles obtuse; ratio length:width = 1:1.4; coarsely, irregularly punctate, with reticulate microsculpture. Elytra of medium length, wider than pronotum, ratio length:width = 1:0.7; with 9 coarsely, closely punctate striae; stria 1 clearly impressed, remaining striae weakly or not impressed; intervals irregularly punctate. Antennal club (
<figureCitation box="[1199,1286,229,255]" captionStart="FIGURES 75–78" captionStartId="29.[151,269,1763,1787]" captionTargetBox="[247,1339,1163,1734]" captionTargetId="figure-395@29.[240,1346,1159,1738]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 75–78. Sogda enigma. 75. Right antenna, dorsal view. 76. Male right protibia. 77. Male right metafemur and metatibia. 78. Aedeagus, dorsal view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Fig. 78), 0.4 mm (Fig. 76), 0.5 mm (Fig. 75), 0.75 mm (Fig. 77)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310939" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310939/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 75</figureCitation>
) moderately broad, ratio club width:length = 1:2.8; width ratio of antennomeres 7:8:9 = 1.3:1:1.7. Mandibles not dissected; apex of right mandible slender, unidentate; apex of left mandible broad, unidentate. Profemur and mesofemur of male unarmed; male metafemur (
<figureCitation box="[575,661,345,371]" captionStart="FIGURES 75–78" captionStartId="29.[151,269,1763,1787]" captionTargetBox="[247,1339,1163,1734]" captionTargetId="figure-395@29.[240,1346,1159,1738]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 75–78. Sogda enigma. 75. Right antenna, dorsal view. 76. Male right protibia. 77. Male right metafemur and metatibia. 78. Aedeagus, dorsal view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Fig. 78), 0.4 mm (Fig. 76), 0.5 mm (Fig. 75), 0.75 mm (Fig. 77)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310939" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310939/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 77</figureCitation>
) with posterior margin serrulate, tooth before apex. Male protibia (
<figureCitation box="[159,246,384,410]" captionStart="FIGURES 75–78" captionStartId="29.[151,269,1763,1787]" captionTargetBox="[247,1339,1163,1734]" captionTargetId="figure-395@29.[240,1346,1159,1738]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 75–78. Sogda enigma. 75. Right antenna, dorsal view. 76. Male right protibia. 77. Male right metafemur and metatibia. 78. Aedeagus, dorsal view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Fig. 78), 0.4 mm (Fig. 76), 0.5 mm (Fig. 75), 0.75 mm (Fig. 77)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310939" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310939/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 76</figureCitation>
) widened and concave dorsally at apex, with elongate, sinuate spur; male mesotibia weakly widened apically; male metatibia (
<figureCitation box="[448,533,422,448]" captionStart="FIGURES 75–78" captionStartId="29.[151,269,1763,1787]" captionTargetBox="[247,1339,1163,1734]" captionTargetId="figure-395@29.[240,1346,1159,1738]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 75–78. Sogda enigma. 75. Right antenna, dorsal view. 76. Male right protibia. 77. Male right metafemur and metatibia. 78. Aedeagus, dorsal view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Fig. 78), 0.4 mm (Fig. 76), 0.5 mm (Fig. 75), 0.75 mm (Fig. 77)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310939" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310939/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 77</figureCitation>
) angulate at about basal one-fourth of inner margin, narrow at base, widened in apical three-fourths; all tibiae spinose on outer margins. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[841,911,461,487]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Male.</emphasis>
Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[1050,1136,461,487]" captionStart="FIGURES 75–78" captionStartId="29.[151,269,1763,1787]" captionTargetBox="[247,1339,1163,1734]" captionTargetId="figure-395@29.[240,1346,1159,1738]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 75–78. Sogda enigma. 75. Right antenna, dorsal view. 76. Male right protibia. 77. Male right metafemur and metatibia. 78. Aedeagus, dorsal view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Fig. 78), 0.4 mm (Fig. 76), 0.5 mm (Fig. 75), 0.75 mm (Fig. 77)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310939" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310939/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 78</figureCitation>
) with median lobe broad, narrowing to very thin, broadly rounded apex. Parameres short, reaching apex of median lobe, slender, with inwardly angled apices and two apical setae. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[680,778,538,564]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Female.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,152,758]" box="[198,1326,576,603]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,359,576,602]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Distribution.</emphasis>
The species is known only from two localities in eastern North America (
<figureCitation box="[1225,1313,577,603]" captionStart="FIGURE 68" captionStartId="27.[151,257,1226,1250]" captionTargetBox="[224,1363,197,1200]" captionTargetId="figure-207@27.[224,1363,197,1200]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 68. Known North American localities of Stereus arenarius (asterisks), Sogda obtusa (black dots), Sogda enigma (open squares)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310933" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310933/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 68</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,152,758]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,675,615,641]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Field notes, habitats and seasonality.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus box="[745,848,616,642]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">holotype</typeStatus>
was taken in a mature maple forest in a flight intercept trap in fall or early winter.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,152,758]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,339,693,719]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Etymology.</emphasis>
The epithet 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peck &amp; Cook" authorityYear="2009" box="[487,573,693,718]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Sogda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="enigma">
<emphasis box="[487,573,693,718]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">enigma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(from Latin 
<emphasis box="[724,825,693,718]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">aenigma</emphasis>
, puzzle) refers to our initial difficulty in the generic placement of this species.
</paragraph>
